'''Jeannot Bemba Saolona''' (born September 1941 [[Équateur (former province)|Libanga]], [[Équateur (former province)|Équateur]], [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]], died 1 July 2009 [[Brussels]], [[Belgium]]) was a Congolese businessman, Minister of the Economy and Industry, and Senator for [[Équateur (former province)|Équateur]].<ref>Tshitenge Lubabu M. K. [http://www.jeuneafrique.com/Article/ARTJAJA2530p040-041.xml0/-deces-senateur-homme-d-affaires-Jeannot-Bemba-Saolona-Jeannot-Bemba-Saolona Jeannot Bemba Saolona] (in French) 6 July 2009, accessed 29 December 2009</ref> His son [[Jean-Pierre Bemba]] became the last [[Vice-President of the Democratic Republic of the Congo]].<ref>[http://congonewsagency.com/?tag=jeannot-bemba-saolona Senator Jeannot Bemba Saolona dies at 67] 3 July 2009 Congo News Agency</ref>
Bemba Saolona's company, [[Scibe Airlift|Scibe CMMJ]], was implicated by the [[United Nations]] in smuggling weapons to [[UNITA]] during the [[Angolan Civil War]].<ref>Johan Peleman, [http://www.iss.co.za/Pubs/BOOKS/Angola/15Peleman.pdf "The logistics of sanctions busting: the airborne component"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070307005934/http://www.iss.co.za/Pubs/BOOKS/Angola/15Peleman.pdf |date=2007-03-07 }}, (PDF file), page 303</ref> He was a close confidant to President [[Mobutu Sese Seko]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/6085536.stm Profile: Jean-Pierre Bemba], BBC News Africa, 25 May 2008.</ref>
