'''Werner Baldessarini''' (born 23 January 1945, in [[Kufstein]] in [[Tyrol (state)|Tyrol]]) is an [[Austria]]n fashion designer and businessman. He was formerly chairman of [[Hugo Boss]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Der Boss wird 60 |trans-title=The Boss turns 60 |url=http://www.stern.de/wirtschaft/news/werner-baldessarini-der-boss-wird-60-535590.html |work=[[Stern (magazine)|Stern]] |date=24 January 2005 |accessdate=14 July 2010 |language=German }}</ref>

==Biography==
Werner Baldessarini is the son of a textile wholesaler, and in turn completed an apprenticeship as a textile merchandiser. He started working in Munich for a Wagenheimer retail store, where he became chief of purchases. In 1975, he joined the company Hugo Boss. He was promoted chief designer and joined Hugo Boss' executive board in 1988.<ref name="fashionmodel bio">{{cite web|url=http://www.fashionmodeldirectory.com/designers/werner-baldessarini/|title=Werner Baldessarini|website=Fashionmodeldirectory.com|accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref> He was asked by the founders of Hugo Boss to drive the growth of the company.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2001/feb/24/2|title=Dressed for success|website=Theguardian.com|date=24 February 2001|author=Andrew Clark|accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref>

In 2002, Werner Baldessarini left Hugo Boss.<ref name="fashionmodel bio"/>

